[Student "E"]
{[showcards N:S4]

You are North. The bidding has been as shown.

Partner led the \H9, taken by dummy's \H10. The \S4 is then played from dummy. Do you play low? or split your honors?

Play the \SJ (or \SQ).

You should always make a point count check as soon as you see dummy. East's 2NT promises 20 or 21 points, West has 14 and you have 3; total = 37 or 38. Therefore South must have either 2 or 3 points. He cannot have two Jacks because you can see all four of them. Likewise he cannot have a Queen because you can see three of them and his \H lead (top of nothing) denied that Queen.

It follows that South <b>MUST</b> have a King, and it must be \Cs or \Ds since he has denied any \H Honor.

Since South will definitely win his King, you need to take one trick yourself, and the best way to do that is to split your Honors to establish one \S winner.

East has no defense to this, but if you had played low he would have played the \ST and made the slam. }
[Play "W"]H9

